metadata.name: Flimsy #33
metadata.description:
This started as an abstract project but the output gradually came to resemble some creatures of the sea like jellyfish and sea slugs. I decided this time to go with the flow and added spines and eye spots to make them look a bit more organic.

Initially this will be a free mint as a reward to the holders of my existing projects. After a day or so the reserves will be removed and the remainder will be available to anyone for a small amount of tezos.

Primary Features:
Layout - Open 40%, Closed 40%, U-Shaped 15%, Radial 5%
Background - Spots 50%, Lines 50%
Spines - true 25%, false 75%
EyeSpots - true 25%, false 75%
Ridges - true 25%, false 75%
Marking - Bands 50%, Stripes 50%

metadata.name: TRQ.1 #39
metadata.description:
The aesthetics of the work is inspired by the work of the Brazilian artist DIONISIO DEL SANTO, above all, the formal simplification, the use of geometric figures, in addition to planes and colors, in a simplified way, the work also makes reference to the principles of Concretism, as a movement artistic.

Features:
PALETTES
In total, the work has fifteen different color palettes, with percentages of probability of occurrence varying between 2% and 15%.

FORMES
The images are structured using only three simple shapes (square, rectangle and triangle) proportional to each other. Said shapes can also be rotated and interleaved with empty squares.
The use of each one of the forms follows three different combination patterns, according to the description and percentages of occurrence indicated below:
“+++” – 50% | full square + triangle
“++” – 35% | rectangle + triangle
“+” – 15% | just triangle

INVERSÉ
One of the rare features, with only a 10% probability, is the occurrence of the inverted color palette, in which the colors of the background, simple shapes and frame, are put in negative.

VECTEUR
The background was structured following two possible direction vectors (horizontal – 40% or vertical – 60%).

MODULES
The canvas can be subdivided following three different modulations, which can be 3X3 (20% chance), 4X4 (45% chance) or 5X5 (35% chance).

September 01, 2022.
Generative token by Paivei made with p5js for FxHash.

metadata.name: The Climb #155
metadata.description:
The climb is about the search for purpose.

Everyone needs a purpose, a path that leads somewhere. Whether you reach it or not is not the point, it’s about the climb. The search for a purpose gives our life meaning. It gives us a reason to look for something more.

Unfortunately, there is no universal truth as to what your purpose in life is. Everyone is unique. Different. We are the product of our upbringing, environment and the cumulative sum of thousands of microdecisions. We need to find meaning for ourselves. Our unique meaning. On this path, we climb alone.

“The Climb” is created to be raw, unique, beautiful and violently volatile, much like our lives.


Everything is written in javascript and p5js.
It can sometimes take a little while to render on older computers.

metadata.name: Symbology437 #87
metadata.description:
Abstract, distorted compositions using symbols from the original IBM VGA codepage 437 character set. The symbols were created in code as bitmaps, scaled, and then drawn onto the canvas. The shading is based on the characters and sets from ANSI and ASCII art styles. 

There are 4 main types of outputs:
- Abstracts, 50%
- Random characters, 25%
- One of 16 preset character layouts, 25%
- One of 16 custom symbol PFP styles that will be 10% of the total outputs

For abstracts, there are several main styles created from layering different base shapes: circles, filled circles, rectangles, flow field lines, and rain-like streaks.

Color combinations include monochromatic, green or amber, dark mode, and multicolor.

Press 's' to save the image. The size is 2318x3000px, and for PFPs, the size is 3000x3000px.

metadata.name: Contraversus #2
metadata.description:
Do opposites attract?

As social beings we create interaction environments, where we inhabit common spaces with other peers, creating micro universes where we feel contained and accompanied.

Can we maintain the fragile equilibrium of these systems that we generate with others?
Or the individuality that identifies us unleashes storms and chaos when the shared places are charged with opposing energies.

Does at some point change the polarity that attracts us and separates us from one another?

These questions sooner or later are part of the nocturnal musings when we withdraw into ourselves to notice our environment at some point in our brief existences.

MAIN FEATURES

5 3d models
20 shapes of external geometries
4 planet size
3 LissaJouseSpline formulas
4 arrays of combinations of numbers possibilities for LJSF
100 color palettes


INTERACTIVITY

Left click = rotation
Right click = reset position
Press Enter key on the canvas = play music
Press number key 1 = mute or enable music
Scroll = zoom in / zoom out

made in cales.gl

metadata.name: Canevach #474
metadata.description:
Canevach started as a code golfing experiment, 280 characters of HTML, CSS and JavaScript producing pixelated patterns when copy-pasted in the address bar of a web browser.

The code has been adapted for the sake of entropy control and readability, but I tried to keep it as lean as possible to honour the code golfing spirit that initiated the project.

The artwork is generated by manipulating pixels directly through the Canvas API.

Colours are uniformly selected in RGB space, without any colour theory considerations. The only exception is for black, which is made more prominent by the way the algorithm is initiated.

Features
• Canvas size: 8x8 | 16x16 | 32x32 | 64x64 | 128x128
• Number of colours: 1 to 5

fx(hash) Generative Token by loackme

metadata.name: Holy Mountain #82
metadata.description:
Mountains throughout human history have taken on deep meanings. Coated with immense sacredness by all peoples in the most different places. Being them as a representation of God himself or being the object of worship. For many the mountains were the very abode of the Gods. They are in the collective unconscious as the ability to connect men and gods, through the flow of energy between earth and heaven.

The symbology is very strong. It unconsciously reminds us of the process of encounter between the loneliness of the earth and the hope of the sky, between the fog that blinds and the cloud that supports, between the abyss of the ground and the proximity of the stars. All this is very charming and fascinating.

All human beings have their own mountain, which demands from each one their limits to reach the top, the desire for the breathtaking view, the fear of falling, but also the hope of the last step at the highest point.

In generative art it couldn't be different, going through all the learning, from its fundamentals, to all the countless hours of tests, to countless moments of problem solving and research and more research. This whole process is without a doubt like climbing a mountain. Thinking about the project is exactly like looking at a mountain and imagining how exhausting it will be all the way to conquer it. Finishing your work is like breathing a sigh of relief, looking down and seeing how hard it was to get there, but at the same time looking ahead and realizing how rewarding it was to be able to have that vision and breathe the refreshing breeze of the moment.

After going through a transformation in my first work, where I transmuted my artistic essence from illustration to generative art. Now I come to this second work that I delved into, and after months of climbing this mountain of mine, I give it to you.


- Press "S" in live view mode after loading to save at 1600x1600px.

license: 
CC BY-NC-ND 4.0

project website:
https://playman.me/projectmountain

metadata.name: The Abstract Truth I  #292
metadata.description:
Moiré patterns meet halftone dots meet cross stitching.

Halftone is a term that can refer to both a technology used in image processing and as the synonym for semitone in music. A jazz musician Oliver Nelson released the album The Blues and the Abstract Truth in 1961. It is considered one of the most significant records of its time. In addition, he wrote Patterns for Improvisation, a hugely popular jazz patterns book. The Moiré pattern design is on the book's cover.

Look out for the FOMO keyboard key to unlock more variations. 
Press 'P' to pause/unpause the animation.
